This feature is created by taking the logarithm of the product of squared age, BMI, and heart rate. The square operation on age captures the nonlinear relationship between age and health risks, while incorporating BMI and heart rate accounts for the combined cardiovascular and metabolic effects. The logarithm transformation helps manage potential non-linear distributions and extreme values in the data.
Calculate the interaction feature between smoking status and heart rate by multiplying the heart rate by the currentsmoker variable. For current smokers, this will amplify the heart rate value, potentially highlighting risks associated with smoking and elevated heart rates.
This feature is calculated by multiplying age, average systolic blood pressure, and average glucose level. It captures the interaction between age and the physiological factors related to blood pressure and glucose, which are critical indicators of cardiovascular health.
